#Text=Wikinews interviews Scott Lucas , Eyal
#Text=Zisser , Majid Rafizadeh about risks of US military intervention in Syria
#Text=Sunday , September 8 , 2013
#Text=File : Prof.
#Text=Scott Lucas 1 . jpg
#Text=File photo of Prof. Scott Lucas . Image : Scott Lucas .
#Text=( Image missing from commons : image ; log )
#Text=The United States President Barack Obama announced last Saturday he was seeking Congressional authorisation for military intervention in Syria .

#Text=Looking for more-qualified input , Wikinews interviewed : professor Scott Lucas , an expert in American Studies , from the UK ' s University of Birmingham ; the President of the International American Council on the Middle East , Majid Rafizadeh ; and , professor Eyal Zisser , a Syrian expert , from Tel Aviv University .
#Text=Discussing the risks involved with US military intervention in Syria , Wikinews posed a range of questions to these experts on the region 's political climate .
#Text=( (
#Text=Wikinews
#Text=) )
#Text=Is it possible for the US to take military action to deter further use of chemical weapons without getting dragged into the civil war ?
#Text=Prof.
#Text=Scott Lucas
#Text=: The US is already involved in the civil war — the question is to what extent .
#Text=The US has given political support to the opposition and insurgency since late 2011 , and from summer 2012 , it has pursued covert support to the opposition fighters .
#Text=However , the Obama Administration has been hesitant about overt support for insurgents throughout the conflict , and that has affected co-ordination of covert efforts .
#Text=In June , the Administration finally said it would provide overt military assistance , but then pulled back and failed to deliver any public aid .
#Text=Had it not been for the August , 21 chemical weapons attack , that position would have persisted .
#Text=Majid Rafizadeh
#Text=:
#Text=It depends on the scope of the military operation .

#Text=If United States conducts limited military operation , as the adminstration argues , and if US only targets some of the Syrian government 's military installments , it is less likely that United States will be drawn into the Syria 's civil war .
#Text=It would be a political suicide for Syria , Iran or Hezbollah to respond .
#Text=On the other hand , if Assad observes that the balance of power is tilting against him inside the country , he might use chemical weapons in the future despite US limited strikes .
#Text=Prof. Eyal Zisser
#Text=: Yes , it[sic ] the attack is limited .
#Text=And If the Americans only use missiles .
#Text=They can cause severe damage , but leave Assad in his palace , and not being dragged into the civil war .
#Text=The United States President Barack Obama with Russian President Vladimir Putin earlier this year .
#Text=Image : Pete Souza .
#Text=( (
#Text=WN
#Text=) )
#Text=Will military intervention from the US affect long term relations between the United States and Russia ?
#Text=SL
#Text=: Of course , significant military intervention by Washington will affect relations between the US and Russia , but the long-term effect cannot be predicted .

#Text=It is dependent on Russia 's reaction — so far , Moscow has been able to pressure the US into caution , but a decision for intervention by the US might call Russia 's bluff , so to speak , and force some caution by the Russians .
#Text=Already , Moscow has said it will not join a fight against any US military action .
#Text=And , of course , the long-term relationship is dependent on the political and military success of any US intervention .
#Text=MR
#Text=: Military intervention , in the classic sense of putting troops on the ground , will definitely affect US-Russian long term political relationships .
#Text=It might heighten the diplomatic tensions .
#Text=However , the limited military operation is less likely [ to ] change US-Russian long term economic , geopolitical , and political relationships .
#Text=EZ
#Text=: No.
#Text=They need each other in many other places of the world .
#Text=Russia knows that the US is a super power and will not be interested in a real conflict with Washington .
